      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The empirical evidence surrounding trickle-down economics is a long-standing and heavily contested topic, with no true consensus. Proponents often cite periods of high GDP growth following tax cuts as proof, while critics point to decades of rising income disparity despite corporate tax reductions. In reality, the data frequently shows that the majority of the benefits from such reforms accrue to the top earners, making the \"trickle-down\" effect largely theoretical in practice.",
      "source": "target",
